Summary: Stellar flares are short-lived, highly energetic events that have lasting effects on planets in their early developmental stages. Young stars (<5 Myr) are ideal targets to study these processes because they provide a snapshot of earliest stages of star and planet evolution. To date, no flare studies of these stars exist. Only TESS can provide the precision, time-sampling, and continuous coverage needed to characterize flare activity on young stars. We propose to obtain TESS two-minute light curves to resolve short-lived flares in a sample of 225 young stars and to quantify the relationship between flare activity and system properties that have not yet been examined, in addition rounding out results from existing statistical flare studies that do not include the youngest stars.
